Introduction¶

  • I am going to analyse long term unemployment rate percentage. It is available in Gapminder

  • Gapminder Dataset link

  • I visit the above link and then select work, and then select unemployment, and then click on long term unemployment

  • I just go through the dataset and click on the yellow color tool like icon, next to the red baloon. That creates a new tab and takes me to gapminder tools. And I see a line graph of long term unemployment percentage of United States and Russia

  • I close the tab. In the tab titled "Download the data | Gapminder" I click on download as XLXS

  • I create a new folder inside my analyst folder, which is inside home. I rename the new folder as "long_term_unemploymnet" I cut the XLXS with name, "long_term_unemployment_rate_percent.xlsx" and place it in long_term_unemploymnet (Please refer revision 1)

  • I go through the dataset for few seconds. I save as .csv file

  • I open up my terminal and open jupyter-notebook and then navigate to the long_term_unemployment folder

  • I rename the jupyter-notebook as "longterm_unemployment_analysis"

  • The data set contains long term unemployment percentage for 122 countries from the year 1990 to 2017 and there are lots of missing values

Questions¶

  • The rate of unemployment percentage over years is increasing or decreasing or it is at a steady rate?
  • Which category of unemployment is more? Lower long term unemployment rate percentage over years is more or higher unemployment rate percentage over years?
  • Whether any country or countries have witnessed or been through all categories or ranges of unemployment over years?
  • What are the country or countries with higher and lower long term unemployment percentage over years?
  • What is the trend of long term unemployment rate percentage of 5 highly economically developed countries?

Problems in the Dataset¶

  • The columns are values and not variables
  • There are lots of missing values

Steps to fix the problem¶

  • Melting the columns. Creating new columns named 'year' & 'percent_unemployment'
  • Filling the NaN/missing value with appropriate values by trial and error method

Preliminary steps¶

  • First I am going to melt the columns using pandas melt
  • And then I am going to multiply the values by 100 so that the values are represented in percentage
  • And I plot the graph with long term unemployment rate for Russia & United States
  • Further, I am going to check whether the results of the graph is similar to the one in gapminder website
  • Gapminder sample graph

Deciding Methods to Fill NaN¶

  • I am going to decide between filling NaN with mean, median or by interpolation
  • If I choose interpolation I am going to decide about using linear or polinamial or spline interpolation
  • I make a copy of the melted dataframe df_melt as df_melt_copy and work with df_melt_copy dataframe
  • Once I decide about filling NaN with any of the above mentioned methods I will make final changes in df_melt dataframe

Out[33]:
2.020680095108696
In [34]:
df_melt['percent_unemployment'].median()
Out[34]:
1.475

Reasons for not filling with Mean or Median¶

  • The mean is more than the median
  • It is clear that the distribution is right skewed, based on histogram, as well as values of both mean and mode
  • Filling NaN with mean or median would mean that 56% of the NaN values will be filled with mean or median
  • For better analysis I am going to fill missing values with linear interpolation

Observations From Using Linear & Polynomial Interpolation¶

  • The linear method will fill all the NaN once I specify limit_direction = 'both'
  • The same is not the case with polynomial interpolation
  • Since the NaN is more than 50% linear interpolation will not result in a better approximation
  • I am going to try spline method and interpolate

Observations From Using Spline Method¶

  • With the default limit_area = None, the spline method results in 5 negative values
  • To fix this I tried using limit_area = 'inside'
  • Limiting area as 'inside' resulted in 5 negative values
  • The negative values occurs as the spline method tries to fit the curve
  • I replace the negative values with the mean

Replacing negative values with mean¶

  • It is not good to replace negative values with 0 or drop it
  • The unemployment percentage of Zimbabwe for the year 2017 will be 0 if I replace the negative values with 0
  • But the unemployment percentage of Zimbabwe for the year 2014 is 2.42 percentage
  • It is more logical to replace these 5 negative values with mean.

Finalizing the method to fill NaN based on graphs and also statistics¶

  • Based on the line graph it is more obvious that spline method tries a lot to fit the data within boundary
  • This results in huge spikes
  • When I compared 'Albania' & 'Zimbabwe' the first and last countries in the 'country' field, spline resulted in lots of spikes
  • The spikes from spline shows that there's huge dip and rise in the unemployment percentage
  • Further, linear method has resulted in almost same results
  • So, based on these graphs alone I couldn't decide about the method to fill NaN
  • I am going to make a decision by plotting a scatter plot

Deciding by plotting box plot and histogram¶

  • The results from spline method vary
  • The purpose is to fill NaN and not simply drop it
  • Spline method can be very useful for sudden spike or drop in values
  • For the scope of the analysis spine method may not be useful
  • I will elaborate more about the scope of the analysis and limitations in Exploratary Data Analysis and Conclusion
  • Most likely I am going to fill NaN with linear interpolation
  • Before that I am going to plot box plots and histograms and convey the reason for filling NaN with linear interpolation

Comparing Observations from Linear, Polynomial, and Spline Interpolation¶

  • The linear and polinomial interpolation produced almost similar histograms
  • The results from both linear and polinomial interpolation is almost identical
  • Theoritically the spline interpolation method will result in less residual error
  • Also theoritically the polinomial interpolation will result in more accuracy
  • But this data was spread towards width and I have reduced the width and increased the depth
  • This analysis is about long term unemployment percentage of 122 countries

Drawbacks of using Polinomial and Spline Interpolation for this Analysis¶

  • All the interpolation methods will have some overlaped values in place of NaN carried over from other countries
  • The analysis is about overall percentage of long term unemployment and for that linear interpolation is sufficient
  • The spline method has too much of values in between 2-3 percentage
  • The major disadvantage of using spline method is that the value will change everytime the code is run
  • Furthermore, both polinomial and linear interpolation will not fill all the NaN
  • So I have to fill the remaining NaN with mean or median, which is not diffcult, but this does not fulfill the very purpose of filling NaN completely
  • Lastly, the spline method will leave some negative values
  • Replacing the negative value from spline interpolation with zero would mean that there was no long term unemployment
  • Or replacing the negative spline interpolation value with mean or median might end up in higher percentage of long term unemployment

Advantages of using Linear Interpolation for this Analysis¶

  • The linear interpolation fills all the NaNs
  • Theoritically it might not be the best method to fill in the NaN
  • But the scope of the project is not to accurately find out percentage of unemployment in a particular country
  • The analysis scope lies in better approximation
  • Even though the distribution is right skewed it is not ideal to replace NaN with median
  • Replacing the NaN with median or mean would mean more than 50 percentage of values are replaced with a single value

Interpretation from Graphs¶

  • The graphs clearly shows that the percentage unemployment rise from 1990, and then goes down towards 2017

Interpretation from Histograms, Box Plots, Scatter Plots¶

  • These shows that the linear interpolation methods fills in the missing values with better approximation
  • Both linear interpolation and polynomial interpolation of one degree shows identical results
  • The spline method tries to produce somewhat even distribution but that results in negative values
  • The scope of data cleaning is only limited to filling or replacing the NaN with better approximation
  • Both the linear and polinomial interpolation produce similar results
  • But polinomial interpolation does not replace all the NaN which is accomplished by linear interpolation
  • Since the analysis is not just about the values I am adopting linear interpolation
  • Walkarounds to fix the issues related to polinomial interpolation and spline interpolation is beyond the scope of the analysis
  • Further explaination of scope is in the exploratory data analysis and conclusion phase

Few More Points on Going Ahead With Linear Interpolation¶

  • The linear interpolation provides better technical assesment to the data
  • Better assesment will lead to better approximation
  • It is better to go ahead with linear interpolation rather than filling with median or mean

Few Important Points about the Dataset that Lead to Choose Linear Interpolation¶

  • I perfomed the tests to choose the method of interpolation on Albania and Zimbabwe
  • For Zimbabwe long term unemployment for the year 2014 alone was present
  • Both linear and polinomial interpolation produced similar results graphically
  • Similar graphical result is sufficient for concluding based on visualization
  • Furthermore, linear interpolation fills in all the NaN when filled in both directions

Observation from cut and qcut¶

  • Both cut and qcut have rendered similar results
  • It is obvious that both will produce similar results
  • While using cut method I need to set the minimum value slightly less than the actual value and maximum value slightly more than the actual value. In bin edges I have set starting edge as 0.014 % instead of 0.0142 %.
  • Similarly I have set the ending bin edge as 14.00001 % instead of 14.000000 %.
  • The reason for choosing starting bin edge slightly less than the minimum value, and the ending bin edge slightly more than the maximum value is that, the cut method cuts based on values "greater than the starting edge and lesser than the ending edge"
  • I will use the dataframe manipulated after performing cut to produce categorical data
  • I am going to make use of pandas crosstab to find out which countries have been through all the ranges of unemployment
  • In order to find out which countries have witnessed all the categories of unemployment I cut it ahead along with qcut

  • The answer to the question is highly dependent on how the unemployment rate is categorized
  • Since I have taken all the countries and all the years into consideration, I have classified 25% and 50% quartile values as high, the higher unemployment percentage is more than the lower unemployment percentage

Observations After Comparing Five Economically Developed Countries Based on HDI¶

  • Comparing long term unemployment percentage of economically developed countries based on HDI gives further insight into the dataset
  • As per the article in the Wikipedia I expected Ireland to fall in the lower side
  • But as per the Gapminder dataset Ireland has highest long term unemployment percentage of the five highly developed countries
  • Most likely it may not be the best method to filter out economically developed countries based on HDI Index
  • Overall, highly economically developed countries have lesser long term unemployment percentage than less developed countries

Conclusions¶

  • Over the years the long term unemployment percentage has been increasing
  • But there is a decrease in long term unemployment of the year 2017 compared to 2010, yet it is more compared to 1990
  • Some countries have seen all ranges of unemployment over years, if long term unemployment percentage is categorized into low, high, higher, severe
  • Countries with higher long term unemployment is more than countries with lower long term unemployment percentage
  • North Macedonia is a country with highest long term unemployment percentage of 14 in the year 2017
  • Philippines is a country with lowest long term unemployment percentage of 0.0142 in the year 2016
  • As per the original dataset the maximum long term unemployment percentage of Philippines was 0.1 in the year 2001
  • Highly economically developed countries have lower long term unemployment rate percentage than less economically developed countries

Limitations¶

  • Some of the percent_unemployment in Philippines in the year was NaN. I replaced those values with linear interpolation
  • Filling NaN with linear interpolation has resulted in long term unemployment percentage of Philippines in the year 2000 to be more than 4
  • The analysis results depend heavily on the method used for filling NaN
  • Further, the Gapminder data is only about registered long term unemployment percentage over the years 1990 - 2017

What might be the reason for data insufficiency?¶

  • Long term Unemployment percentage of highly economically developed countries are available to larger extent
  • But for some countries long term unemployment percentage for only one year is available, for example, Zimbabwe
  • Determining whether there is a bias in data or not is not the scope of analysis
  • But in Gapminder it is clearly mentioned that it is the data of only registered long term unemployment percentage
  • It is still only puzzling, I could not figure out why long term unemployment percentage for some countries are not at all available and only data for very less number of years is available for some countries
